The paper deals with discrete integration problems, which are often studied in the subfield of theoretical computer science known as computational complexity (cs.CC). The use of random hashes and optimization techniques also suggests a connection to algorithms and data structures (cs.DS). The problem of computing the partition function of a ferromagnetic Potts model is a classic problem in statistical physics, which has connections to both computer science and mathematics, and is often studied in the subfield of discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The use of an NP-oracle and integer linear programming (ILP) solvers suggests a connection to artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the experimental simulation results suggest a connection to machine learning and statistical inference (cs.LG).
